Flames shot from Thassalin's mouth as the huge Thraki set a particular piece of forest ablaze and then circled overhead to detect movement. Strangely enough, the eerie screeching behind him ceased as he slowed down. Thassalin had forgotten the passengers on his back.
"What's this, Tenuk, you've already transformed into a Thraki before!"
"It's completely different when I fly myself, than being suddenly lifted by a huge pink dragon!"
"It wasn't that bad, was it, Kayel?"
Kayel was obviously not in agreement with Nyssi. He looked less grim than usual and his claws had dug so deep into Thassalin's back that the Thraki was bleeding. Thassalin apparently didn't mind this. Nevertheless, he had realized that he had scared his new friends and landed in a clearing.
“I’M SORRY, BUT I SMELLED SOMETHING. I HAD TO TAKE CARE OF THAT!”
“But did you have to drag us along too?” growled Tenuk as he climbed down from Thassalin's back and slid down his tail. “And we left Retvik behind! We abandoned our big, strong fighter! How will he ever catch up to us?”
“He’ll figure something out…,” growled Nyssi. “Retvik isn’t the fastest, but he’s not stupid.”
“True, but can Retvik drive?”
Nyssi winked and turned back to Tenuk. “Of course he can drive.”
“Have you ever seen Retvik drive a vehicle? He doesn’t have a truck like you, and I haven’t even seen him drive a nice little car like Kayel’s. Plus, he only started taking the car to work because you always drive us. He only has his bicycle.”
Loud laughter interrupted her. Thassalin suddenly found something incredibly funny, but no one knew what he was laughing at. It took a bit too long for Thassalin to calm down.
“I’M SORRY, BUT I IMAGINED YOUR GIANT FRIEND IN ARMOR ON SUCH A TINY LITTLE BIKE FOR TEMTHAN KIDS. THAT WAS HILARIOUS! I WISH I HAD SOME KIND OF TELEPATHY. A WONDERFUL IMAGINATION! ONE I CAN’T SHARE!”
Kayel chuckled, as he could imagine what was going on in Thassalin’s mind. “Yeah, that’s true. But what did you smell, and why did you suddenly take off?”
Thassalin grunted, took off, and disappeared. When he returned a short while later, he threw something lifeless at Nyssi’s feet. It was an Orothrack, a very rare, gold-white dragon creature. But it was missing its head. “ANOTHER DEAD ONE. I HEAR THEIR SCREAMS. SMELL THEIR BLOOD. SOMETHING DRIVES ME TO PROTECT AND HUNT. AS YISINI COMMANDS. THEY ARE VERY CLOSE.”
The mighty Thraki suddenly froze. Nyssi and Kayel also froze and looked attentively toward a gap in the clearing. Something large and black stared at them and hissed. Whatever it was, it spread two enormous pairs of wings and shot toward Thassalin, not caring about the three smaller beings between them. Kayel and Tenuk just managed to take cover, but Nyssi was dragged along and almost thrown onto Thassalin.
Thassalin reacted to this attack by grabbing Nyssi and hurling him onto his back with his incredibly long, skillful tail before swinging himself into the air. The black, double-winged creature pursued them at high speed.
Kayel snapped angrily while he took his rifle from his back and opened a bag containing a belt of ammunition. He hung the belt over his chest, but quickly realized that Nyssi, the Thraki, and the monster were out of sight.
“Hey, Tenuk, could you transform into something that can fly?” asked Kayel.
“You want to chase them?”
“Yes, of course!”
“But… One of them is a huge monster!”
“So what? I’m standing here with a top-of-the-line rifle in my hand and could shoot immediately. But, well, how should I put it – I would have to be able to see it in order to hit it.”
Tenuk hesitated, then stepped back to make more room. With a soft, painful grunt, Tenuk’s body stretched out, his fur turned into scales and his arms into wings. He quickly transformed into a normal, bright blue Thraki, but his eyes remained red.
“Get on.”
Like an otherwise ordinary Thraki, Tenuk now had a neat scale armor running along his back. Practically, however, a pair of spines had also grown on his back, which Kayel could hold onto. It took a little too long for Tenuk to get the flight started, but once in the air, he quickly oriented himself and tried to resume the pursuit.
Tenuk and Kayel quickly realized they were not alone. A second dark creature shot up beneath them, and Tenuk could only barely avoid a collision.
"That's probably the other terrifying giant monster that Lanex was afraid of?" Kayel frowned. He tried to shoot at the second beast, missed, and quickly reloaded.
Tenuk did not respond. He was too occupied with focusing on the flight toward Nyssi and Thassalin, even though the other creature was pursuing them. Kayel awkwardly turned around to keep an eye on the monster. The fact that it was pursuing them was an advantage for Kayel, because it made it easier for him to aim and fire. Two shots went through the upper wings of the beast. It roared in pain and sank back under the trees. Kayel was not sure if it was still following them, but it certainly would not be able to keep up with them.
A good distance ahead of them, Nyssi was desperately clinging on, while Thassalin was flailing and spitting flames at the blackened monster. The creature was definitely injured. It seemed extremely angry, but not willing to give in. The fireballs did not seem to have the desired effect. As Thassalin stretched, Nyssi took the opportunity to draw her own weapon, an old but reliable shotgun. It was not exactly the first choice, but perhaps the shot would scare the black beast away.
